steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"dbok2","text":"  ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"6lfuv","text":"Check the microscope to be sure it is clean. You are responsible for the condition of the microscope at the close of your session.If you find it dirty, make sure microscopy staff know about it; that is, email, phone us or by leaving feedback on the sheets provided. ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7mt11","text":"Check the eyepiece dioptre settings. If you don’t need to make an adjustment for your vision, set both to zero. Set the interpupillary distance for comfortable binocular viewing.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"c619a","text":"Log in to the computer, using your UQ-SSO credentials.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"for7p","text":"Press the (grey) power button on the bottom left hand side of the microscope stand and wait for the LCD on the microscope to finish loading.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"g0f6","text":"Start the acquisition software, ZEN, by double-clicking the ZEN desktop icon.   ","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":32,"length":3}],"entityRanges":[{"key":1,"offset":78,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"cohic","text":"Please be patient: ZEN is a large program and takes a while to load and start. Double-clicking numerous times will not make this process go any faster and may, in fact, prevent it starting. Note that you may also start ZEN by right-clicking on the ZEN icon and selecting Open from the resulting menu.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":271,"length":4}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"fn05q","text":"If you are using a template to image specific wells, calibrate the stage position.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"b45cl","text":"Objectives – always inspect and clean oil immersion objectives both before and after a session. Note only clean the objectives by using a lens wipe, do not use any solutions or solvents.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":68,"length":6},{"style":"bold","offset":79,"length":5}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9p50n","text":"Always double check the LCD touchscreen, ZEN software or the objective itself to confirm which immersion media should be used on each objective; Dry or Oil.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"t062","text":"Fluoro 2 has both Dry and Oil Objectives.Note:","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":46}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6a25n","text":"            Dry (these never have media applied): 5x, 10x, 20x. 40x.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":23,"length":5}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"45dm","text":"            Oil: 63x, 100x ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ed2jl","text":"        Do not apply too much oil to the slide and objectives; one drop will suffice.Be sure to cleanthe oil off the objective between samples.Apply fresh oil for each sample.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":8,"length":77}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"24lj7","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"1uqbl","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ce0l9","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4crv1","text":"ZEN has four basic interface screens, accessed via tabs toward the top left of the display.Locate is used when finding the object of interest through the eyepieces or via the camera system. Acquisition provides for set up of imaging provisions, and image capture.These are most used during routine imaging, and will be covered in the user tutorial.The other two screens, Processingand Analysis, provide various methods of post capture image modification and characterization, respectively.Contact microscopy staff for instruction in these functions.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":91,"length":7},{"style":"bold","offset":190,"length":11},{"style":"bold","offset":371,"length":10},{"style":"bold","offset":385,"length":8}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4thf6","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5l6pr","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"image","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"4E75D620502911ED82048F9167B577BF","height":436,"id":305733,"is_video":false,"legend":"","mime":"image/png","original_name":"image.png","placeholder":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jkuhbm7s7.jpg","source":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jkufbm7s7.jpg","type":1,"webp_placeholder":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jkugbm7s7.webp","webp_source":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jkuebm7s7.webp","width":409}},"1":{"type":"image","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"5CB35050502911ED82048F9167B577BF","height":121,"id":305737,"is_video":false,"legend":"","mime":"image/png","original_name":"image.png","placeholder":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jkumbm7s7.jpg","source":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jkujbm7s7.jpg","type":1,"webp_placeholder":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jkukbm7s7.webp","webp_source":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jkuibm7s7.webp","width":119}}}}

Note: the edges of the slide must be slid under the silver retention clips.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"c344g","text":"Move the eyepiece/camera slider on the right side of the microscope head into the eyepiece position (“in”).","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3vjj9","text":"Click on the Locate tab (3).","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"biahe","text":"Select the illumination method, brightfield, DIC, or dye you wish to image, by pressing one of the favourite buttons (4) that most closely matches your own dyes emission colour.\n a.\tQuad DAPI/GFP/mCherry/Cy5 are excited by individual LEDs and are detected through a quad-band emission filter, which can result in bleedthrough/crosstalk, when you can see fluorescence from a neighboring channel in the channel of interest but acquisition is fast.\n b.\tBP DAPI/GFP/mCherry/Cy5 are excited by individual LEDs and are detected through individual band-pass emission filters, which results in no bleedthrough but is slower.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"c8moe","text":"Using the joystick, locate a region of interest in your sample. F1 toggles the XY speed between slow and fast.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cquvt","text":"Carefully bring your sample into focus using both the course and fine focus nobs on either side of the microscope.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5uvhg","text":"Switch to whichever objective you wish to use.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cdlcg","text":"Move the eyepiece/camera slider on the microscope to the camera position (“out”).","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"aetl","text":"Click the Live button (5), to see the live camera image on the computer display.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6hl1j","text":"Click the Find Focus and Set Exposure (6) buttons to adjust the focus and exposure of the image, or adjust the exposure manually using the Exposure Time slider.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"98fu3","text":"Optionally, increase the image resolution by changing the binning to 1x1 (7), then adjusting the exposure again.","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2gvfv","text":"If you are collecting single colour images, you may now simply click the Snap button to capture an image (8), or use the dropdown tab to capture a quick tile of your sample (9).","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"loud","text":"Click Save (10).","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"image","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"26CA9270502711ED82048F9167B577BF","height":580,"id":305741,"is_video":false,"legend":"","mime":"image/png","original_name":"image.png","placeholder":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jkurbm7s7.jpg","source":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jkupbm7s7.jpg","type":1,"webp_placeholder":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jkuqbm7s7.webp","webp_source":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jkunbm7s7.webp","width":550}}}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"1s1iq","text":"Close the Field Stop (two small buttons on the right-hand side along the base of the stand) and bring the image of the Field Stop into focus using the Condenser Focus Wheel (found below the stage but above the Specimen Focus Wheel).","type":"ordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":10,"length":11},{"style":"bold","offset":151,"length":21},{"style":"italic","offset":180,"length":5},{"style":"italic","offset":200,"length":5}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2cqeq","text":"            i.Centre the image of the Field Stop in the field of view using the sub-stage condenser centering screws.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ava4j","text":"            ii.Open the Field Stop until it is just beyond the field of view.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":47,"length":4}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"53pkv","text":"   2.Set the Aperture Stop to a value of three-quarters of the numerical aperture of the objective (0.75 × AN, for the               mathematically minded).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":13,"length":13},{"style":"sub","offset":108,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"fedoq","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

Select Apotome from the experiment dropdown list. 
3. Check that the Apotome is Active, If there is a red X, make sure Apotome is in position. If there is a red X next to      4. Channel Calibrated, contact microscopy facility staff.
5. Select the tickboxes for Channels you wish to image.
6. Move the eyepiece/camera slider on the microscope out to the camera position.
7. Click the Live button, to see the live camera image on the display. 
        Note the Apotome blocks a lot of light and you will need to re-set exposure values when using this method.
8. Click the Find Focus and Set Exposure buttons to adjust the focus and exposure for all of the Channels of the image, or manually click on each Channel to highlight it, then adjust the exposure manually using the Exposure Time slider.
9. Increase the image resolution if desired by changing the binning to 1x1, then adjust the exposure again.
